# Text Elements
 ^1w4bptOI

//init semaphore lockB to 0
//init semaphore lockA to 0
//both semahores would have max_count = 1
void P1(void)
{
    wait(&lockB);
    //Statement A
    signal(&lockA);
}


void P2(void)
{
    Statement B
    signal(&lockB);
}

void P3(void)
{
    wait(&lockA);
    //Statement C
} ^Ntf0CRaa

To trace this, 

P3 starts, attempts to acquire lockA, fails and sleeps
P2 starts, finishes statement B and signals on lockB and exits
P1 starts, attempts to acquire lockB and succeeds
P1 does statement A and signals on lockA and can signal on lockB too to free it
P3 is awoken and acquires lockA
P3 does statement C and returns (and can signal lockA as well to free itself of it

at the end, all locks can be freed as well ^h1QmW4X8

All share a pointer to a stack based variable but since this variable is shared between
all the threads, there was a race condition to read it and the main thread did not wait for
the thread to finish before incrementing since the main thread and the child threads execute
concurrently and it cannot be determined which order they will execute. Thus, when i = 0, 
even though the thread was spawned, it had not executed until  main thread updated i 
the first thing printed was not 0 but 1, and then the next thread executed could not print 
i until main thread incremented i to 3 thus the remaining threads printed 3

There are two ways to solve this
1 is to pthread_join in the first for loop 

OR

create an array of ints and pass a different pointer to them
such as 
int nums[4];

for(i = 0; i<4; i++)
{
    nums[i] = i;
    pthread_create(&tid[i], NULL, foo &nums[i]);
}

that way, there will be no race condition since each thread gets their own pointer to a unique
value, not a shared value with main ^4ReudDTJ

Output:

2
3

OR

1 ^XsHEWdbN

Scenario 1 = System is underutilised as low CPU and disk utilisation s (likely small number of IO bound processes) that didn't
load more processes so low utilisation. Increase multiprogramming degree

Scenario 2 = System is likely thrashing. Many processes loaded thus needing to swap pages in and out of memory often OR, processes
kept changing working sets and thus had to keep paging disk. Decrease multiprogramming degreee

Scenario 3 = System is not thrashing and just being used highly. processes may be CPU bound and thus take a lot of CPU
usage and processes may be in their working set. Do not change multiprogramming degree. ^z1LMLgNW
